[{"id":"FT561654","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n<img alt=\"The figure shows a diagram of two conducting spheres and a positively charged rod. The two spheres are positioned side by side and touching, and are equal in size. The rod, represented by a vertical rectangle with 6 positive signs, is positioned to the left of the spheres.\" height=\"266\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/media.academicmerit.com/af9083beceb3819b54372c28a6a104d1/original.png\" width=\"371\">\n<p>Two uncharged conducting spheres on insulating stands are in contact when a positively charged rod is brought near but does not touch them, as shown in the figure above. The right sphere is then moved far to the right, and finally the rod is removed. Which of the following best shows the final distribution of excess charges, if any, on the spheres?</p>","choicesHtml":["<img alt=\"The figure presents an uncharged sphere.\" height=\"97\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/media.academicmerit.com/22695657afa245b524acaee4996a7665/original.png\" width=\"250\">","<img alt=\"The figure presents a sphere with 6 negative charges.\" height=\"75\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/media.academicmerit.com/4f607942fbb58b4b29a75ed5801935d9/original.png\" width=\"250\">","<img alt=\"The figure presents a sphere with 6 negative charges.\" height=\"74\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/media.academicmerit.com/70cc144f56e10ec2c9129cc4aee8873b/original.png\" width=\"250\">","<img alt=\"The figure presents a sphere with 6 positive charges.\" height=\"74\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/media.academicmerit.com/1628eaf42498747edfde0b1edd884c17/original.png\" width=\"250\">"],"answer":1}]